english:
  title: Preface to Poems Sent to Great Zen Master Hu upon His Assumption of the Dharma Joy Society
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In ancient times, those who studied Zen would ascend to Master Touzi three times and journey to Dongshan nine times, traversing a thousand li back and forth without rest—for they sought to test their understanding against those of clear sight, casting off their own limited views until their minds aligned in perfect accord. Thus was their diligence such as this. In this present age, should one measure up to those ancients, such a one would have no cause for shame—and is this not our Great Zen Master Hu?

    The Master, having already risen through the monastic ranks and earned renown throughout the monastery forests, went directly to Maple Mountain to perfect his own practice. At that time there appeared in the Western Regions a certain Master Zhikong, who compared himself to the Patriarch Bodhidharma with such splendor that the people rushed about vying to perform the rites of discipleship. The Master came to test him. Zhikong declared, "When I burn an incense stick, you shall flee; when I give a shout, you shall return." The Master answered, "Let the honored teacher go first—I shall follow with my staff." The disciples saw this as lacking in respect and sought to respond with rudeness, but the Master merely brushed his sleeve and departed without a backward glance.

    Thereupon he journeyed northward to the capital, and southward through Jiangzhe, the Two Cantons, Sichuan, Gansu, and Yunzhou—enduring years of heat and cold, visiting every place under heaven. As his vision grew expansive, so his foundation became solid. As his verification became clear, so his resolve grew firm. Then he returned with ease and abided in tranquility. Those who had doubted now felt ashamed; those who had mocked now bowed.

    The Master said, "Those who doubted and mocked—can they truly be called wrong? Those who feel ashamed and now submit—can they truly be called right? Right and wrong are determined by others; I myself cannot know them." Word of this reached the throne, and the Master was held in even greater esteem. He was appointed to lead the Dharma Joy Society.

    The various scholars, taking the couplet by Su Dongpo—"His body traveled ten thousand miles, half the world below; the monk rested in one hermitage and saw his head turn white"—used these phrases as rhyme to compose fourteen poems as a gift for the Master's travels. The Master then requested the Hermit Ikjae to inscribe a preface. But the Hermit, being very aged, how could such writing be expected of him?

    In the Tang dynasty, when Wen Chang sought commendations from famous lords and ministers to sing the praises of great persons, posterity retained only the prefaces of Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan. Chancellor Sima Guang selected only a few words from Han Yu—for their directness and propriety. Wen Chang was merely one who delighted in eloquent words; how could the Master be compared to him? Do the various scholars' poems truly capture his spirit? Can the Hermit Ikjae's words adequately answer his request? A Sima Guang—such a one cannot be found in this world. Should one appear, would the Hermit Ikjae's words find his approval? The Hermit himself cannot know. Thus do I smile and write this down.
  footnotes:
    - 'Touzi and Dongshan: Famous Zen meditation centers whose names reference the Buddhist journey of enlightenment-seeking; ''nine times'' and ''three times'' suggest the devotion required of serious practitioners.'
    - 'Bodhidharma: The legendary founder of Chan/Zen Buddhism credited with bringing Buddhist teachings from India to China.'
    - The Master's refusal to obey Zhikong's display of power reflects Zen's skepticism toward flashy demonstrations and preference for genuine realization.
    - Su Dongpo's couplet itself became famous as it expresses the spiritual transformation that comes through extensive pilgrimage and practice.
    - 'Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan: Tang dynasty literary figures whose commemorative writings were considered models of proper praise.'
    - 'Sima Guang: A renowned Song dynasty statesman and historian, invoked here as an example of truly discriminating judgment.'
